        <div class=3D"section collapsed" id=3D"section-pre-header-section">=
<div class=3D"section-container"><p><strong>Continued fractions</strong> ha=
ve been studied for over two thousand years, with one of the first recorded=
 studies being that of Euclid around 300 BC (in his book <em>Elements</em>)=
 when he used them to find the greatest common divisor of two integers (usi=
ng what is known today as the <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/euclide=
an-algorithm/" class=3D"wiki_link" title=3D"Euclidean algorithm" target=3D"=
_blank">Euclidean algorithm</a>).</p>

<p>Since then, <strong>continued fractions</strong> have shown up in a vari=
ety of other areas, including, but not limited to,</p>

<ul>
<li>rational approximations for real numbers</li>
<li>solving <a href=3D"https://brilliant.org/wiki/linear-diophantine-equati=
